The United States Capitol, also known as the Capitol Building or the U.S. Capitol, is the home of the United States Congress, the legislative branch of the federal government of the United States. It sits on Capitol Hill at the eastern end of the National Mall in Washington, D.C. Originally only housing the United States Senate in its northwest wing, with the U.S. House of Representatives meeting in the Old Brick Capitol, it later came to house both houses of Congress as the Capitol building expanded.

The Capitol has a central dome over a rotunda, with wings to the north and east for the Senate, and to the south and west for the House of Representatives. The Capitol is located on a hill between Maryland Avenue and Virginia Avenue (north-south), and First Street and Third Street (east-west). It is within the Capitol Hill Historic District. The Capitol is open seven days a week, from 8:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., except for federal holidays.

The building is constructed primarily of sandstone from a quarry in Maryland. The exterior walls are constructed of marble from a quarry in Georgia. The original plan for the Capitol was designed by Dr. William Thornton, and the exterior was designed by Benjamin Henry Latrobe and Charles Bulfinch. The design is a classic example of the neoclassical architectural style.

The Capitol building has undergone many changes and expansions over the years. The original Capitol building was much smaller, and it was only one story high. It was expanded in 1850-1856 with the addition of the north and south wings. The dome was constructed between 1855 and 1866. The current Capitol building has a total floor space of 15.5 million square feet.

In addition to the Senate and House chambers, the Capitol building contains office space for members of Congress and their staffs, committee meeting rooms, and public rooms. The Capitol is also home to the United States Supreme Court, which was housed there from 1800 to 1935, when the Supreme Court building was constructed on the north side of the Capitol grounds. The building is also used for other functions, such as the presidential inauguration, state funerals, and other ceremonial events.

The Capitol building is a symbol of the United States government and is a popular tourist destination. The building is also home to the National Statuary Hall, which contains two statues from each state, and the United States Capitol Visitor Center, which provides information about the Capitol and the legislative process. The Capitol is one of the most recognized landmarks in the United States and is featured in many works of art, photography, and film.